The '''Ilchamus''' (sometimes spelled Camus or Iltiamus, also known as Njemps), are a Maa-speaking people living south and southeast of [[Lake Baringo]], [[Kenya]]. They number about 35,000 and are closely related to the [[Samburu people|Samburu]] living more to the north-east in the [[Rift Valley Province]] They are said to be the smallest ethnic group in Kenya. Their language is one of the [[Eastern Nilotic languages|Eastern Nilotic]] [[Maa languages]], closely related to the [[Samburu language]] (between 89% and 94% lexical similarity), to the point of it being considered a Samburu dialect by some. Together, Samburu and Ilchamus form the northern division of the Maa languages.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Non-Bantu languages of Kenya. (Language and Dialect Atlas of Kenya 2)|last=Heine|first=Bernd|publisher=Dietrich Reimer|year=1980|isbn=|location=Berlin|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Eastern Nilotes. Linguistic and historical reconstructions (Kölner Beiträge zur Afrikanistik 9)|last=Vossen|first=Rainer|publisher=Dietrich Reimer|year=1982|isbn=|location=Berlin|pages=}}</ref>

In their oral traditions, the Ilchamus economy underwent a succession of elaborations: from foraging and fishing to a sophisticated system of irrigation, and then this was mixed with pastoralism under the influence of Samburu immigrants and neighbouring Maasai. These changes involved a series of embellishments in their culture and social organization.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Pastoral Continuum: the Marginalization of Tradition in East Africa|last=Spencer|first=Paul|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1998|isbn=|location=Oxford|pages=129-203}}</ref> However, this evolving system did not survive the challenges of the capitalist economy in post-colonial Kenya, leading to a more polarized society with diminishing prospects for the majority of Camus.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Elusive Granary: Herder, Farmer and State in Northern Kenya.|last=Little|first=Peter D.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1992|isbn=|location=Cambridge|pages=}}</ref>

