{{infobox person |name =Kanam EJ |birth_name =Elavunkal Joseph Philip |birth_date =13 June 1926 |birth_place =Kanam, Kottayam district, Kerala |occupation =writer |death_date ={{death date and age|1987|6|13|1926|3|13}} }} '''Elavunkal Joseph Philip''' ({{lang-ml|ഇലവുങ്കൽ ജോസഫ്‌ ഫിലിപ്പ്‌}}) (13 June 1926 – 13 June 1987), popularly known by his [[pen name]] '''Kanam EJ''', was a [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] novelist, [[short story]] writer, and lyricist. Along with his contemporary, [[Muttathu Varkey]], he was known for his stories written with the common man in mind.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mohan Lal|first= |title=The Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature |year=1992|publisher=[[Sahitya Akademi]]|isbn=81-260-1221-8}}</ref> Philip started the well known [[Malayalam]] weekly ''Manorajyam'' and served as its editor.
==Early life and career== Philip was born on 13 June 1926 as the son of Elavunkal Joseph in [[Kanam]], a small village in [[Kottayam district]] of [[Kerala]]. He attended MHSS [[Kangazha]] and passed Malayalam Higher. After schooling he joined military service. He return to [[Kottayam]] after the military service and joined CMS Middle School Kanam, as a teacher. Later he served as Malayalam Pandit in CMS schools of [[Mundakayam]], [[Kumpalampoika]], [[Punnavely]] and [[Kottayam]]. Philip quit teaching and joined the popular Malayalam Weekly [[Malayala Manorama]] as a journalist. In 1967 he resigned from Malayala Manorama and started his own Malayalam Weekly called ''Manorajyam''. He later sold it to George Thomas of ''Keraladwani''.
===Literary career=== Kanam emerged as one of the popular writers of Malayalam fiction during the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Azhikode |first=Sukumar |title=Malayalam short stories: an anthology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XlkKAQAAIAAJ&q=muttathu+varkey&dq=muttathu+varkey&num=100&pgis=1 |year=1972|publisher=[[Kerala Sahitya Akademi]] |accessdate = 2011-03-29|isbn=978-0-471-92452-4}}</ref> He mainly wrote social novels based on the Christian community of [[Kerala]].<ref>{{cite book |last=R. Leela Devi|first= |title=History of Malayalam literature|year=1977|publisher=Educational Supplies Depot.|isbn=}}</ref> He was a prolific writer and has written about 100 novels. Almost all of his novels were published in serial installments (''Neendakatha'') in [[Malayala Manorama]] Weekly. One of his novels, ''[[Bharya (1962 film)|Bharya]]'', was adapted into a [[Malayalam film]] with the same title. The 1962 film was directed by [[Kunchacko]] and starring [[Sathyaneshan Nadar|Sathyan]] and [[Ragini (actress)|Ragini]].<ref name=hindu_dec11>{{cite news|title=Bharya (1962)|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article2726313.ece|accessdate=3 March 2012|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=18 December 2011}}</ref> Kanam also wrote lyrics to few Malayalam films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://malayalasangeetham.info/php/createMovieIndex.php?encode=utf&m_year=&m_musician=&m_director=&display=Search&submit=Search+For+Movie+Names&m_comments=&m_writers=Kanam EJ|title=MSI Malayalam Movie Lyricist Kanam EJ |publisher=malayalasangeetham.info| accessdate=2011-03-29}}</ref>
===Death=== Kanam died on his 61st birthday in 1987.
